entry.title: CodeHealth: Switch WebApp::operator== to from make_tuple to tie.
entry.content:
std::make_tuple actually makes a copy of all of the arguments, which is

unexpectedly expensive for an equality check. It was done to avoid a

dangling reference to the string created by SerializeAsString().

A better solution is to go back to std::tie and define an equality

operator for the WebAppOsIntegrationState proto.



I'm a little dubious about using SerializeAsString to compare protos as

I believe this includes deprecated/unknown values but leaving it

unchanged in this CL.

entry.title: [MirrorSync] Fix use after free on SyncStatusTracker
entry.content:
The issue was caused by a combination of 3 bugs:



1. Instead of only setting ids to leaf nodes, ids were set to all

nodes inserted to the trie to insert the desired path;



2. The case where a existing node is overriden with a new id

wasn't being handle at all (likely to happen during file dances);



3. The id of a node was not being reset to 0 (invalid stable_id)

when its corresponding path was detected to have been moved.



The combination of those 3 bugs could lead to a scenario exemplified

by the newly added unit test where, in summary, a series of operations

would lead to an entry in id_to_leaf_ pointing to a node that had

already been deleted.



Bug: b:276784178

Test: chromeos_unittests SyncStatusTrackerTest.*

entry.title: [Ash Pixel Diff] Use positive if only algorithm - part 1
entry.content:
This CL implements PositiveIfOnlyImageAlgorithm. It is similar to

ExactSkiaGoldMatchingAlgorithm but this matching algorithm expects

that the benchmark image group has only one image. In contrast,

ExactSkiaGoldMatchingAlgorithm allows the benchmark image group to

have more than one images.



We will use PositiveIfOnlyImageAlgorithm as default in ash pixel tests

so that developers have to change the revision number in code to

update benchmarks.



This CL applies PositiveIfOnlyImageAlgorithm to DemoAshPixelDiffTest

by adding the test name to the list under ash_pixel_differ.cc.



Subsequent CLs will migrate the remaining pixel tests.

entry.title: Don't include group-targeted field trials in metrics reports
entry.content:
This adds an is_low_anonymity property of FieldTrials, and by default

does not return these to callers (in GetActiveFieldTrialGroups() and

via Observers). Callers which specifically want to read the low

anonymity trials must do so via FieldTrialListIncludingLowAnonymity.



This also includes a change to move away from the deprecated

`base::LazyInstance`, required to avoid a build failure as a

side-effect of this CL (see crbug.com/990948).



Bug: b/274900786

entry.title: [iOS] Make ContentWebFrame keep a pointer to its RenderFrameHost
entry.content:
ContentWebFrame stores GlobalRenderFrameHostId identifying its

corresponding RenderFrameHost. However, during

ContentWebFramesManager::RenderFrameDeleted, this id has already

been deregistered and can no longer be used to find the

RenderFrameHost, even though the RenderFrameHost still exists (though

is about to be destroyed).



SharedPasswordController calls into ContentWebFrame::IsMainFrame

and ContentWebFrame::GetSecurityOrigin during RenderFrameDeleted,

so ContentWebFrame needs to be able to access the RenderFrameHost

inside these calls in this situation. Since lookup by id cannot

work here, this CL instead stores a pointer to the RenderFrameHost.



Storing a pointer is safe, since the ContentWebFrame is deleted at

the end of RenderFrameDeleted, and this is before the RenderFrameHost

gets destroyed.

entry.title: Add support for boosting the priority of the first N images
entry.content:
At parse time, images default to a low priority which puts them behind

any async scripts before them in the document and behind all blocking

scripts, including those at the end of the document.



In ~40% of the cases where the LCP element is an image in the HTML

markup, ~80% of the time the LCP image is one of the first 5 images

in the document (60% are one of the first two). See the referenced

crbug for more analysis details.



This allows for boosting the priority of some number of images that

are discovered in the HTML markup to a medium priority which will

put them ahead of async scripts as well as any blocking scripts that

come after them in the markup.



This also exposes a param to allow for some number of medium-priority

fetches to be in-flight while the scheduler is in "tight" mode

independent of the total number of in-flight requests. By default,

medium-priority requests are scheduled the same as low-priority

requests and are only sent if there are no more than 2 other requests

pending in total.



The goal of the experiment is to see if we can improve FCP and LCP

without degrading DOM Content Loaded.
